Three technical reasons for the speed increase:

1. Swap File Recovery
At 3 GB free, macOS could not allocate sufficient swap space for virtual memory. It was compressing RAM aggressively and delaying writes. With 38 GB free, swap files expand and contract freely. App switching and multitasking are now immediate rather than stuttering.

2. SSD Garbage Collection
SSDs (your "Flash Storage") require free blocks for wear leveling and TRIM operations. At 2.5% capacity, the controller struggles to find empty cells, causing write amplification and read latency spikes. At 30%+ free, the NAND controller operates in its optimal performance envelope. This is measurable, not placebo.

3. Cache Efficiency
While you deleted 10 GB of caches (which forces apps to rebuild them temporarily), you eliminated cache thrashing. When the disk is nearly full, macOS wastes CPU cycles constantly evicting and recreating cache entries to make room. With space abundant, caches stabilize.

Warning: You may notice a slight slowdown over the next 48 hours as caches rebuild (browsers re-download assets, apps regenerate indices). This is temporary. The underlying I/O performance gain from adequate free space is permanent.

